04390nam a22005055i 9780520927957DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20032004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209279577 a10.1525/97805209279572doi  a(DE-B1597)519813  a(OCoLC)1114893762  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aB3248.G34bG37 2004eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a19322200aGadamer's Repercussions :bReconsidering Philosophical Hermeneutics /cBruce Krajewski. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (334 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. From Word to Concept -- tChapter 1. After Historicism, Is Metaphysics Still Possible? -- tChapter 2. Being That Can Be Understood Is Language -- tChapter 3. On the Coherence of Hermeneutics and Ethics -- tChapter 4. Gadamer and Romanticism -- tChapter 5. Literature, Law, and Morality -- tChapter 6. A Critique of Gadamer's Aesthetics -- tChapter 7. On Dialogue -- tChapter 8. Gadamer's Philosophy of Dialogue and Its Relation to the Postmodernism of Nietzsche, Heidegger, Derrida, and Strauss -- tChapter 9. Meaningless Hermeneutics? -- tChapter 10. Radio Nietzsche, or, How to Fall Short of Philosophy -- tChapter 11. The Art of Allusion -- tChapter 12. On the Politics of Gadamerian Hermeneutics -- tChapter 13. The Protection of the Philosophical Form -- tChapter 14. Salutations -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCertainly one of the key German philosophers of the twentieth century, Hans-Georg Gadamer also influenced the study of literature, art, music, sacred and legal texts, and medicine. Indeed, while much attention has been focused on Gadamer's writings about ancient Greek and modern German philosophy, the relevance of his work for other disciplines is only now beginning to be properly considered and understood. In an effort to address this slant, this volume brings together many prominent scholars to assess, re-evaluate, and question Hans-Georg Gadamer's works, as well as his place in intellectual history. The book includes a recent essay by Gadamer on "the task of hermeneutics," as well as essays by distinguished contributors including Jürgen Habermas, Richard Rorty, Gerald Bruns, Georgia Warnke, and many others. The contributors situate Gadamer's views in surprising ways and show that his writings speak to a range of contemporary debates-from constitutional questions to issues of modern art. A controversial final section attempts to uncover and clarify Gadamer's history in relation to National Socialism. More an investigation and questioning than a celebration of this venerable and profoundly influential philosopher, this collection will become a catalyst for any future rethinking of philosophical hermeneutics, as well as a significant starting place for rereading and reviewing Hans-Georg Gadamer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aKrajewski, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520927957.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles